Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   SEF Official Says Decreased Ties With Mainland `Inevitable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SEF Official Says Decreased Ties With Mainland `Inevitable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1306080394 Taipei CNA in English 0727 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306080394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 13 (CNA) -- Taiwan's government and 
private sectors are gradually reaching a consensus on slowing 
down contacts with Mainland China, Hsu Hui-you, deputy 
secretary-general of the Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) said 
Monday [13 June]. 
  Hsu said that the change in mainland policy is inevitable in 
light of the Qiandao Lake incident, which has once again exposed 
the nature of the Beijing regime and their ideas about 
cross-Taiwan Strait relations. 
  Hsu, a career attorney, said the recent trial of three 
suspects involved in the Qiandao Lake murders was so speedy and 
so simple that the whole process was not only "coarse" but also 
"immoral." 
  Taiwan was denied a say in the trial, hsu said, adding that 
the case early on turned from the criminal to political and 
needed a political solution. 
  Hsu said Taiwan residents have been too hasty to develop 
close ties with the mainland since the 40-year ban on 
cross-strait contacts was lifted. The hastiness is 
understandable, he said, as the Taiwan people could not help 
themselves in the face of eager calls from the "homeland," and 
seemingly unlimited business opportunities, he said. 
  Stricken with "mainland fever," Hsu said, Taiwan residents 
forgot to remind themselves of the huge difference between the 
two sides of the Taiwan Strait and the fact that Beijing has 
never renounced its threat to take Taiwan by force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

