<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Companies To Be Coached in Shareholding Operations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Companies To Be Coached in Shareholding Operations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1206054894 Beijing CHINA DAILY (BUSINESS WEEKLY) in 
English 12-18 Jun 94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> HK1206054894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY (BUSINESS WEEKLY) </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Shuang Mu: "`Coaching' Intended To Ensure Safe </F>
Listings"] 
  [Text] China is creating a framework for coaching 
companies that want to publicly issue stock and be listed on 
exchanges. 
  To ensure the quality of listed companies, the securities 
authorities now require enterprises to accept a six-month-long 
coaching by relevant departments before they publicly issue and 
list shares. 
  The coaching programme is intended to help enterprises 
convert their operations to those of shareholding companies, 
said Sun Xiaoliang, president of the China Shareholding Company 
Consulting Co. 
  Sun noted that shareholding has spread rapidly in recent 
years. 
  By the end of 1993, 189 State companies had become listed 
companies. 
  But some have not substantially changed their operational 
systems. Instead, they still conduct business under the 
original system and regulations. 
  According to the initial instruction plan, said Sun, the 
coaching period will be divided into two stages. 
  The first stage is to be finished before companies issue 
shares to the public. 
  This stage will focus on establishing new corporate systems 
that will make the enterprises responsible for their financial 
losses and profits. 
  The second stage, to be completed before companies are 
listed, will mainly examine the newly established corporate 
systems to ensure that they are put into effect, while studying 
problems in how they are run. 
  As to what kind of institutions are qualified to coach 
enterprises, Sun thinks they should have the following 
characteristics: 
  Firstly, they should understand precisely the purpose of the 
reform of the State economic system. 
  Secondly, they should be quite familiar with the substance 
of 
the various economic reforms. 
  Thirdly, they should fully grasp the policies, regulations 
and details of the modern corporate system. 
  Finally, they should have experience in helping enterprises 
transform their operational systems. 
  The institutions' qualifications should be formally examined 
by the China Securities Regulatory Commission and the State 
Commission for Economic Restructuring. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

