<DATE1>  11 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qiandao Lake Murders Trial Ends 11 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qiandao Lake Murders Trial Ends 11 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1106074394 Taipei CNA in English 0715 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106074394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Yang Hui-chen and Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Hangzhou, June 11 (CNA) -- The trial of the three 
men charged with robbing and murdering 32 people, including 24 
Taiwan tourists, aboard a boat on Qiandao Lake March 31 ended 
here Saturday [11 June], with the verdict to be delivered on 
Sunday. 
  The judge heard the last statements by the prosecutor, the 
defendants and their lawyers before he closed the hearing, which 
began Friday and lasted for two hours Saturday morning. 
  The three defendants -- Wu Lihong, Hu Zhihan, and Yu Aijun 
-- 
all pleaded guilty Friday. 
  No relatives of the Taiwan victims appeared at the court to 
protest Beijing's decision to limit access to the trial. 
  Beijing agreed to allow victims' relatives to attend the 
trial, but barred Taiwan reporters, lawmakers and Straits 
Exchange Foundation (SEF) officials. Taiwan reporters were 
permitted to watch the trial via closed-circuit television. SEF 
is a semi-official organization authorized by Taiwan to handle 
private exchanges between the two sides in the absence of 
official contacts across the strait. 
  In Taipei, eight relatives of the victims held a news 
conference Friday, saying the trial was another attempt by 
Beijing to cover up the crime. 
  "Whatever the result of the trial, we will never accept it," 
a relative told reporters. 
  The Qiandao Lake incident occurred on March 31 when 32 
people 
were murdered and robbed aboard a pleasure boat ferrying them 
across the Zhejiang Province lake. Beijing did not publicize 
the incident until two days later and did not admit the deaths 
involved foul play until Taiwan threatened to review fragile 
cross-Taiwan Strait ties. 
  Beijing then arrested the three suspects and a fourth 
implicated in the incident and made public the alleged 
investigative report which many here said has raised more 
questions than it answers. 
  Different accounts of the incident have since emerged, with 
the latest one coming from legislator Parris Chang, a member of 
Taiwan's largest opposition group, the Democratic Progressive 
Party. 
  Chang told a recent seminar that the murder was carried out 
by a squad of some 10 People's Liberation Army soldiers who were 
executed shortly after the incident. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-25657 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi113_v_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Views Trial of Qiandao Lake Suspects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Report Views Trial of Qiandao Lake Suspects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1306083694 Taipei CNA in English 0722 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Yang Hui-chen and Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Hangzhou, June 13 (CNA) -- All three men charged 
with robbing and murdering 32 people, including 24 Taiwan 
tourists, aboard a pleasure boat on Qiandao Lake March 31 were 
sentenced to death by the Hangzhou intermediate people's court 
Sunday [12 June]. 
  The verdict, delivered during a 30-minute ceremony, 
completed 
the trial, referred to by victims' relatives in Taiwan as a 
"sham" and "nothing but a skit." 
  Announcing the verdict, prosecutors said the suspects robbed 
the tourists, killed them and blew up the boat. They called the 
crime serious and handed down two death sentences for each of 
the three men. 
  The evidence in the case, the prosecutors said, included 
reports prepared by public security police, written testimonies 
by witnesses and a videotape owned by a murdered Taiwan tourist 
discovered at the home of Wu Lihong, one of the three suspects. 
  According to Mainland China's criminal codes, the three 
defendants -- Wu Lihong, Hu Zhihan, and Yu Aijun -- have three 
days to appeal their sentences. 
  The fourth suspect, Wu Liming, who was prosecuted on charges 
of harboring goods stolen in the attack, was sentenced to three 
years in jail Monday. Wu Liming is a military police officer 
and the elder brother of Wu Lihong. 
  Huang Chin-kun, one of the victims' Taiwan relatives, called 
the death sentences predictable. However, he said, many 
questions raised by the relatives and Taipei's Straits Exchange 
Foundation (SEF), a conduit for communications between the two 
sides of the Taiwan Strait, remained unanswered. 
  None of the Taiwan relatives appeared at the court to 
protest 
Beijing's decision to limit access to the trial and they did not 
want to give the impression that they were endorsing the 
verdicts, which they said they "will never accept." 
  Chuang Shu-fang, another relative, said judging from the 
videotapes of the trial, she doesn't believe the three suspects 
are the real murders. 
  The tapes showed that Hu Zhihan consulted his notes when 
answering questions and Wu Lihong even smiled during the trial. 
"How can a murderer forget what he has done and smile at a crime 
as heinous as this one," Chuang asked. 
  After the trial, SEF's Deputy Secretary-General Hsu Hui-you 
expressed his indignation at the mainland's continuing refusal 
to talk with SEF about compensation for victims' relatives and 
signing an agreement securing Taiwan travelers' security in the 
mainland. 
  The Qiandao Lake incident occurred on March 31 when 32 
people 
were murdered and robbed aboard a pleasure boat ferrying them 
across the Zhejiang Province lake. Beijing did not publicize 
the incident until two days later and did not admit the deaths 
involved foul play until Taiwan threatened to review the fragile 
cross-Taiwan Strait ties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

